body:
@vahidhashemian Thanks for the patch. I think there's some details we should sort out as far as how this patch affects commit semantics. For example, if the user changes their subscription and immediately calls `commitSync()`, do we expect that offsets for the unsubscribed partitions should be committed? Or do we expect this patch to only affect autocommits? 

I'm also wondering about an alternative implementation which avoids the additional complexity in `SubscriptionState` by sending an asynchronous commit in `KafkaConsumer.subscribe()` prior to changing the subscription when autocommit is enabled. Maybe that would be a simpler if we only expect this patch to affect autocommit behavior?

@becketqin Thoughts?

@hachikuji One minor note, but LGTM
Also, replication tests are look healthy in this branch: 
http://confluent-kafka-branch-builder-system-test-results.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/2016-05-11--001.1462947131--hachikuji--KAFKA-3694--50630af/report.html

@hachikuji Thanks for your detailed explanation. They way I understand your alternate approach (and correct me if I'm wrong please) is that the [`subscribe()` method](https://github.com/apache/kafka/blob/trunk/clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java#L829) would be changed to something like this:

```
    @Override
    public void subscribe(Collection<String> topics) {
        if (!subscriptions.assignedPartitions().isEmpty())
            commitAsync(subscriptions.allConsumed(), null);
        subscribe(topics, new NoOpConsumerRebalanceListener());
    }

```

Except that the auto commit status has to be checked there too (I haven't figured out yet how the consumer can see the auto commit status, which is in the coordinator).

@vahidhashemian Yeah, that's what I was thinking, though the check in `subscribe()` would probably just look like this:

``` java
if (autoCommitEnabled)
  commitAsync();
```

The `autoCommitEnabled` flag comes from configuration.
